title: For Sale:  Factory CZ82 or CZ83 Slide Complete with Front and Rear Sights Extractor, Firing Pin and Recoil Spring will Not Fit 32 ACP
postcontent:
Our # CZPT8201FP

At least, we don’t think this slide will fit a 32 ACP caliber CZ83. This slide is part of the last of our Knoxville neighbors’ last hurrah of the excellent little CZ-82 Pistols that came in a couple years back. The parent pistols were produced in the late 1980s, some of the best in the world. Original chambering for these is the hot little Makarov Round, the 9x18 caliber. The slide and magazine will work just fine with the CZ-83 pistols, but only the ones chambered in 380 ACP caliber. At press time, we had the few remaining CZ82s and their twelve round magazines listed mostly on Guns America, search terms CZ82 Robertson. This listing is for One Slide, but winning buyers may take any number of extras we have on hand at the same per-slide price and with no additional shipping charges. Photo specimens are part of this lot of only a couple dozen remaining parts guns that TGI had left. All of them are matte black finish with moderate edge whitening. We rate them as Good, perhaps Very Good, and buyers will receive one of the photo specimens or one of its mates from the same batch of 25 some odd that we had at press time. Construction is all steel, with serrated rear area and serrated rib on top of the slide. This slide assembly is entirely original CZ, Czeska Zbrojovka, made in the Czech Republic in Strakonice. Importer is Tennessee Guns, TGI of Knoxville, and each slide is importer stamped inconspicuously on its forward bottom edges. These slides are excellent mechanically. All parts are included with the slide. Replacement pricing on a CZ slide is upwards of $200 from many sources. We’re offering the factory CZ82 CZ83 Slides in the photos, however, or their identical mates each for only $ 99.00.

Our # CZPT8220

This internal part comes from the final specimens of the excellent little CZ-82 Pistols that came in a couple years back. The parent pistols were produced in the late 1980s, some of the best in the world. Original chambering for these is the hot little Makarov Round, the 9x18 caliber. Dimensions, however, are the same for the model 83 pistols chambered in .32 ACP and .380 ACP; and this factory ejector will function on the model 82, and both variants of the CZ83. At press time, we had the few remaining CZ82 pistols themselves and their twelve round magazines listed mostly on Guns America, search terms CZ82 Robertson. This listing is one part, the ejector. Winning buyers may take any number of ejectors we have on hand at the same per-ejector price and with no additional shipping charges. Photo specimens are part of this lot of only a couple dozen remaining parts guns that TGI had left. All of them are original steel with minimal edge whitening on the top edge of the ejector proper. We rate their finish as Very Good, and buyers will receive one of the photo specimens or one of its mates from the same batch of 25 some odd that we had at press time. Construction is all steel. This part is entirely original CZ, Czeska Zbrojovka, made in the Czech Republic in Strakonice. Importer is Tennessee Guns, TGI of Knoxville. These parts are excellent mechanically. title: For Sale:  HK MR762A1 .308/7.62mm NIB
postcontent:
This rifle is located at U.S. Firearms Academy.  This item is subject to sales tax for NV residents and a 25.00 fee for the background check.  

Like its 5.56 mm counterpart, the MR762A1 is a direct descendent of the HK416/417 series, only in a semi-automatic rifle configuration developed for civilian users.

Using the HK-proprietary operating system, the MR762A1 is gas operated and uses a piston and a solid operating “pusher” rod in place of the common gas tube normally employed in AR15/M16/M4-style weapons.

Pioneered by Heckler & Koch in the G36, HK416, and HK417; this method virtually eliminates malfunctions common to direct impingement gas systems since hot carbon fouling and waste gases do not enter the receiver area. The MR762A1 stays cleaner, reducing heat transfer to the bolt and bolt carrier, and drastically reducing wear and tear on other critical components. The service life of all parts is increased substantially.

The MR762A1 uses a barrel produced by Heckler & Koch's famous cold hammer forging process. This manufacturing process uses the highest quality steel, producing a barrel that ensures superior accuracy, even after firing thousands of rounds. The MR762A1 is produced at Heckler & Koch's American manufacturing facilities from both American and German-made components.

The MR762A1 uses many of the assemblies and accessories originally developed for the HK416/417 series including adjustable buttstocks, ergonomic pistol grips, mechanical sights, and the HK free-floating four-quadrant rail system/handguard. This MIL-STD-1913 “Picatinny” type rail system allows all current accessories, sights, lights, and aimers used on M4/M16-type weapons to be fitted to the MR series. The HK rail system can be removed without special tools by the user and ensures 100% return to zero when reinstalled.

Ambidextrous operating controls are standard on the MR762A1, including a convertible charging handle and an ambidextrous selector lever. The MR762A1 uses the same 10- and 20-round translucent polymer box magazines made for the HK417; a 5-round magazine is also under development. MR762A1 rifles are well-suited for a variety of applications including law enforcement tactical, police patrol, general sporting, and hunting (a 5-round magazine is under development).

Introduced in January 2012, the MR762A1’s Suggested Retail Price is $3,995.

title: For Sale:  7.62x54R Ammo - Assortment Russian Match & Sniper 105rds Best Made
postcontent:
Here's a 105 total round assortment from my personal collection that represents the very best of Russia's Match Grade and Sniper 7.62x54R ammunition from over the years.

All of this ammo was produced at Novosibirsk Low Voltage Equipment plant (LVE) which is where all of their highest quality ammo is produced. All ammo made at LVE bears the head stamp "188" and the year of production. 

LVE is recognized world wide for their superior quality ammunition. Their Match and Sniper ammunition uses special powders, primers and bullets. Plus much more care is taken producing it. The results speak for them self and you'll be amazed at just how much more accurate this high quality ammo really is.

Included: 

(1) still sealed 25 round box of brass case 182 grain Match ammo from 1965 - head stamp 188-65. 

(2) 20 round bundles of 7N1 ammo loaded in annealed copper washed steel cases with a special 152 grain boat tail bullet. Bullet has a steel core followed by a dead air space with a lead knocker in the base. When bullet hits it's target the lead knocker shifts forward destabilizing the bullet resulting in a devastating wound. This ammo was specifically designed for the Dragunov, but it's excellent for Mosins too. Head stamp 188-97.

(1) 20 round box 182 grain Extra Match (blue box) ammo from 1971. Ammo is loaded in brass cases with match powder and match grade bullets. It's extremely accurate and has won many matches over the years. Head stamp is 188-71.

(1) 20 round box LVE 200 grain Extra Match. This is very hard to find and offers superior accuracy - especially at extreme ranges. With the 200 grain bullet it's also the hardest hitting 54R available. Head stamp is LVE 10.

All of this ammo has been stored properly and is in excellent condition. It's all sure fire and you will be surprised by it's accuracy.

$105 picked up in the Brandon area or I can ship via UPS ground at buyers expense. You must be at least 18 to purchase.
